{{Orphan|date=December 2012}}
'''Face of Canada''' is an [[art exhibition]] displaying paintings of notable Canadians. It was showcased on July 1, 2011 at [[Canada Place]] in [[Vancouver]], displaying over 100 [[Oil paint|oil]] [[Portrait painting|portraits]] of notable individuals, both past and present, that helped shape the nation.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://vancouversun.com/life/food/Canadian+artist+open+Vancouver+Canada+exhibit+featuring+portraits+famous/5026251/story.html |title=Canadian artist to open Vancouver Canada Day exhibit featuring 100 portraits of famous Canadians |publisher=Vancouversun.com |date=2011-06-29 |accessdate=2011-08-22}}</ref>
==Artist== The concept was derived by Canadian artist, [[William Meire]]. Born in [[Vancouver]], September 2, 1966, Meire traveled to 49 countries studying art.<ref name="gallery">{{cite web|url=http://williammeiregallery.com/ |title=William Meire Art Gallery |publisher=Williammeiregallery.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-22}}</ref> Painting [[Impressionism|impressionist]] landscapes professionally, in an array of mediums over the past 10 years, Meire turned his interest to portraiture work in oil. After seeing [[Canada men's national ice hockey team|Team Canada]] win the men's [[hockey]] in the [[2010 Olympic Games]] and feeling a sense of national pride, he started the 'Great Canadians,' a small series which eventually led to the Face of Canada.<ref name="gallery"/> After much research, Meire realized the great number of notable Canadians who have shaped and changed the nation, and affected many lives. On July 1, 2011, crowds came to see the one-day solo exhibition of over 100 oil portraits at Canada Place, which has now become part of Canada's national heritage.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://theprovince.com/entertainment/Face+Canada+exhibit+draws+Canada+crowds/5036685/story.html |title=Story - Entertainment |publisher=The Province |date= |accessdate=2011-08-22 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110912122824/http://www.theprovince.com/entertainment/Face+Canada+exhibit+draws+Canada+crowds/5036685/story.html |archivedate=2011-09-12 |df= }}</ref>
==Subjects== The exhibition includes numerous portraits, including:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ctvbc.ctv.ca/gallery/html/bc_famous_faces_1106029/photo_0.html |title=CTV British Columbia - Canada's famous faces on display - News Photo Gallery |publisher=Ctvbc.ctv.ca |date= |accessdate=2011-08-22 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110905080230/http://www.ctvbc.ctv.ca/gallery/html/bc_famous_faces_1106029/photo_0.html |archivedate=2011-09-05 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metronews.ca/vancouver/local/article/904702--getting-face-time-with-some-famous-canadians |title=Metro - Getting face time with some famous Canadians |publisher=Metronews.ca |date=2011-06-30 |accessdate=2011-08-22 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
